# 6.
chi = chisq.test(df$New.Owned.,df$Subdivision)
chi
## 
##  Pearson's Chi-squared test
## 
## data:  df$New.Owned. and df$Subdivision
## X-squared = 40.108, df = 2, p-value = 1.953e-09
## Since the pValue is less than 0.05 this indicates there is sufficient 
## evidence to conclude that the observed distribution is not the same as 
## the expected distribution. I can conclude that a relationship exists 
## between the variables. The variables are not independent. I reject the
## NULL hypothesis.

# Dunes West has the largest standard deviation. 

# The most luxurious PPS is in Dunes West.
# The cheapest PPS is also in Dunes West.

means = a10[,7]
sds = a10[,8]
cv_cp = (sds[[1]]/means[[1]]) * 100
paste(c("Carolina Park CV: ", cv_cp, " %"), collapse="")
## [1] "Carolina Park CV: 13.1977512712666 %"

## [1] "Dunes West CV: 26.1082568365276 %"

## [1] "Park West CV: 22.6360208581618 %"
# Dunes West has the largest Coefficient of Variation.

# 10.

tr = subset(df, df$House.Style=="Traditional")
to = subset(df, df$House.Style=="Townhouse")
sg = subset(df, df$House.Style=="Charleston Single")

par(mfrow=c(1,3))

boxplot(tr$new, main = "Traditional", ylab = "PPS",col = "lightgreen")
boxplot(to$new, main= "Townhouse", ylab="PPS", col="green3")
boxplot(sg$new, main="Charleston Single", ylab="PPS", col= "darkgreen")

# The PPS distribution for Traditional styled homes is slightly right skewed.
# The PPS distribution for Townhouse styled homes is approximately normal.
# The PPS distribution for Charleston Single styled homes is also right skewed.

# 11. 

par(mfrow=c(1,1))
colors = unclass(df$Subdivision)
colors = replace(colors, colors=="Carolina Park", "green")
colors = replace(colors, colors=="Park West", "blue")
colors = replace(colors, colors=="Dunes West", "lightblue")
plot(PPS~df$Acreage, col=colors, pch=19, xlab="Acreage", ylab="$ Price Per Sq/ft", main="Acreage VS PPS")
legend("topleft", c("green","blue","lightblue"), legend=c("Carolina Park", "Dunes West", "Park West"),
       fill=c("green","blue","lightblue"))

cor1 = cor(PPS~df$Acreage)
cor1
## [1] 0.5578637
# There is a strong positive linear correlation between the PPS and the Acreage.

library(ggplot2)

p1 <- ggplot(b3, aes(x=Acreage,y=new, color=factor(Bedrooms))) +
  geom_point() +
  stat_smooth(method = lm) + annotate("label",x = 0.55,y = 330,label = "Regression line: y = 71.11x + 188.89")

p1 + labs(x = "Acreage", y = "PPS", title = "PPS based on Acreage", subtitle = "3 Bedroom Homes")
